---
// The invisible-fields feature strip — the homepage's pointer to the /evidence example family.
// Twelve real-data pages where the field runs with no particle swarm: the measurement comes back
// as type, ink, and anchor. The roster (slug/name/hook/href) is the same one the family's sidebar
// reads (lib/invisible-fields.ts). Each item is an ordinary link made a light attractor, so the
// homepage's visible field — the one page that has particles — gathers on whichever example you
// engage. Styles in styles/invisible-strip.css (global, like manual.css).
import { INVISIBLE_FIELDS } from "../../lib/invisible-fields";
import "../../styles/invisible-strip.css";
---

<section class="concept ifs" id="invisible-fields">
  <div class="wrap">
    <span class="concept-no">invisible fields — live, over real data</span>
    <h2>Everything above shows the field. These twelve never do.</h2>
    <p class="ifs-lede">
      Twelve ordinary page types — an inbox, a market, a backlog, a front page — run as fields
      over <strong>real data</strong>: no particle swarm, the measurements come back as type,
      ink, and anchor. Each ships its data as a committed snapshot, upgrades itself to live
      counts when the source is reachable, and says which mode it's in.
    </p>
    <div class="ifs-grid">
      {
        INVISIBLE_FIELDS.map((f) => (
          <a class="ifs-item" href={f.href} data-body="attract" data-strength="0.5">
            <span class="ifs-name">{f.name}</span>
            <span class="ifs-hook">{f.hook}</span>
          </a>
        ))
      }
    </div>
    <p class="ifs-more"><a href="/evidence">See the family →</a></p>
  </div>
</section>
